# Atomic Commits

## Principle

One commit = one logical change. A reviewer should understand the full intent from the diff alone.

## Hard limit

**≤ 15 files per commit.** If a feature touches more, split into sequential commits:

1. **Data layer** — types, interfaces, DDL, data loaders
2. **Backend** — workers, parsers, shared utilities, Edge Functions
3. **Frontend structure** — new routes, page skeletons, data bindings
4. **Frontend UI** — styles, layout, responsive, animations

## When to split

- Adding a parser AND updating frontend display → 2 commits
- DDL migration AND worker that uses new columns → 2 commits
- Stripe integration AND paywall UI AND pricing page → 3 commits
- Multiple unrelated bug fixes → 1 commit per fix

## When one commit is OK

- Parser + its test file (same logical unit)
- Component + its CSS changes (same visual unit)
- Type change + all files that consume that type (mechanical refactor)

## Rationale

Giant commits (30-74 files) make it impossible to:
- Review changes
- Bisect bugs
- Revert a single feature
- Understand project history
